Juggernaut and Hulk and brush them off.) while not an easy fight for Goku,

beyond, base form Goku would get his ass kicked by Spidey easily as Spidey

Transmission and Solar Flare are actually useless on Spidey thanks to his 
Spider Sense as he has shown he can fight without his eyes.

armor Iron Man is done as underneath he is a flesh and blood human with 
normal human durability. In the armor it could go either way but Goku would 
have to go all out to have a chance and would have to capitalize on any 
openings he could get, something he doesn't always do thanks to his love of 
fighting and wanting to have good fights. Ironically Goku's good nature may 
actually cost him the fight vs Iron Man

universe easily.Either case Goku would have to actually try and Ghost Rider 
couldn't use his Penace Stare on Goku.
- Goku vs Thor - Thor wins no matter which version of Goku is used. Goku

amazing battle.﻿

See, its bad enough when you put characters up against each other in their 
own universe, once you start crossing them, then that's when the shit 
really hits the fan. There is no real definitive way to prove decisively 
which one fictional character is better than another fictional character. 
The winner would be whoever the writer wants to win. I think people often 
forget this is all fiction we are discussing. That means that anything can 
happen should the writers see fit to make it happen.

People can generate all the numbers they want and dig up all the source 
materials they want and toss out ridiculously bold accusations for the sake 
of debate. The bottom line is, they are all fictional characters that exist 
in their own universe. People will decide whoever they decide they want to 
win, doesn't make them right, doesn't make them wrong. 

Captain American can beat Goku; If that's what the writers want then they 
will find a way to make it work. Goku can beat Thor, Superman, Hulk and 
whoever, if that's what the writers want, again they will make it work.

Its all subjective to the viewer. Pick who ever you want, that doesn't make 
you wrong, but it doesn't necessarily make you right either. But go on and 
debate...or whatever this comment section counts as debate; because all of 
it means nothing as there is no definitive answer.﻿

+lenguy45 That's pretty much just like saying "Why debate at all because 
nothing really matters?". You debate because it's fun. Numbers and feats 
are the only way you can prove who has a better chance. There are high 
showings, low showings, and a number of things you have to consider to 
determine the victor. While most of this comment section is just yelling, 
it's pretty dumb to write off the entirety of vs. debates simply because 
there's never one answer. Ever wonder why people say "X would likely beat Y 
7/10 times" or something to that degree? It's because outliers have to be 
taken into account. Nothing is certain, but that doesn't mean probability 
suddenly becomes null. If you don't enjoy debating, then don't do it, but 
don't shit on it for people who do enjoy it. It's like if I came up to you 
and said something along the lines of "Why have fun when you're just going 
to die, anyway?". Simple. Because it's fun and nothing more. Yeah, it's 
meaningless, but so is pretty much everything else, in the end. Doesn't 
mean you can't squeeze enjoyment out of it if it doesn't impede the 
happiness of others.

already planet-shattering attacks by 20 times, JUST BECAUSE?!?! The

SUPPOSED to be too powerful for his own good, thats how Dragonball works.

rise above. Marvel heroes face different struggles, and since Watchmen, the 
Post-Modern American comic book hero has faced their own inner struggles 
which inhibit their power, and ultimately they dont even have to win 
anymore, (ex. Red Son.) Goku HAS to win, its part of his storytelling, (ex. 
Freiza fight.) They arent the same, just because they are both Graphic 
Print doesnt mean they are even the same genre.﻿

+Samuel Rogers That's the thing, future events and alternate timelines are 
really the only ways to explain events that don't happen in the main canon, 
and are wildly irrelevant. I could just as easily say that the entire DB 
verse gets taken down by the Amalgam brothers (read up on them if you don't 
know who they are) but they're not part of the main continuity and cause 
contradictions in the universes of DC and Marvel.

I'm talking about *Kid Buu* , you know, the one who actually blew up earth. 
Fat nor Super Buu were relevant to my argument. Kid Buu, upon regaining his 
original form, blew up Earth within 5 minutes (the clip is here on 
youtube). Hell, even when he was searching for Goku and Vegeta, he was 
blowing stuff up planet by planet without even coming into contact with 
other inhabitants (that clip is also here on youtube).

You don't have to be a superfan to be knowledgeable on a group of 
characters from a company, manga, or story. I'm fully aware of the DB 
character's power, but I wouldn't classify myself as even a regular fan 
because I don't watch DB related stuff regularly anymore aside from DB 
Super from time to time.

You *did* make something up. I advise you to read your comment again, when 
you clearly said Goku fought Meta Cooler (with an army of them fighting 
with Vegeta) in an instant transmission battle. That never happened.

I wasn't insinuating that they could fight forever, just that they don't 
naturally get stronger *during* a fight. They get stronger *through* 
fighting, yes, but the same could be said for nearly every protagonistic 
character in a shonen ever.

Once again, Goku has never moved "infinitely fast", instant=/= infinite. 
Infinite literally means endless, unlimited, *immeasurable* . "Instant" is 
a measure of time, where no time passes between point A and point B. 
Infinite goes *beyond* that. I also never said the Flash is the only being 
who can achieve such speeds, I said he ran so fast that he reversed time, 
effectively going faster than "instant". The Flash can also outrun Death, 
which Goku is not able to do, so infinite speed is well out of his grasp.

To conclude my response, I'm not implying that you have to know the limits 
of *all* the marvel or DC characters, to the contrary, just the ones you 
mentioned. Thor at his strongest is a universal level being, the Silver 
Surfer is literally one of Goku's worst matchups (not only is his speed 
MFTL, he can absorb energy (ki attacks), has cosmic senses, can augment his 
physical strength to well beyond that of any DB protagonist, and is near 
indestructible (he regularly zips in and out of stars as massive as the sun 
and larger, taking absolutely no damage). Galactus isn't even a debate, he 
simply makes Goku's atoms into jello, or plays around with his soul. Keep 
in mind Galactus has made two stars go out just by passing by, and he was 
nowhere near full power

not and never was a "super saiyan god" or busted a galaxy. Same for Buu. 
Kid Buu was innately evil, but he blew up earth without antagonizing 
anyone, so the "he wanted to torture people" argument doesn't work.

You not knowing the true extent of the Surfer is proof in of itself is 
proof that you are not aware of the power of Marvel's inhabitants.

Goku has never moved "infinitely" fast, the fastest he's ever gone is 
instant with the help of instant transmission. You completely made that 
situation with Meta Cooler up, as soon as the army of Cooler's arrive and 
slide down the movie cuts to Goku and Vegeta being captured.

That's false. There's no evidence to suggest that saiyans grow stronger 
during a fight (in fact, the opposite is true). The super forms are rare 
occasions, they're the exception and not the rule. If this was true, Goku 
wouldn't have struggled so much against Raditz, Cell, Kid Buu, and Beerus. 
He actually had Piccolo there to help him with Raditz and still died 
because the only way they could win was him sacrificing himself to keep 
Raditz in place for Piccolo to hit him, gave up against Cell (don't use the 
"he wanted Gohan to fight" excuse, he admitted he couldn't keep up) as well 
as Beerus (he couldn't even beat him with his own power, had to obtain a 
new form from siphoning the energy of others), and clearly stated, when he 
was talking to Vegeta, that he couldn't destroy Buu because he let the 
battle drag on for too long (very clearly indicating he was losing power, 
not gaining it). 

I'm just going to educate you a bit. Flash has moved faster than "instant" 
on a number of occasions, effectively going back in time. The Surfer, as I 
said, is around 32 *million* times faster than the speed of light. Thor 
once punched someone so hard it opened a black hole. The newest superman 
flew from Earth to Pluto and back in a matter of minutes. These are mid 
tiers in the hierarchy of Marvel and DC comics, and they, at full power, 
would eviscerate Goku.  I'm not underestimating DB warriors, I'm saying 
they've never shown the capacity to be able to destroy anything more than 
solar systems all at once, move faster than a few times light without 
assistance, and withstand anything other than ki blasts or physical hits.
